                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Thinking \/ playing with the idea of building discrete simulations using a command line -> GLSL viewer pipeline.\n\nI've built a simple set of tools that allow me to send GLSL code to a browser-based viewer.\n\nI used vanandrewngueyn's "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "https:\/\/github.com\/vanandrewnguyen\/GLSLExperiments\/blob\/main\/Cellular%20Automata\/gameOfLife.glsl",
                                "text": "game of life code"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " and whittled it down to fit the pipeline tools, for testing.\n\nThen, I asked Claude to build code to simulate a Brusselator in the same way. At first, it built code based on differential equations. This shows something interesting in the viewer. Then I asked for code to perform a discrete simulation, but, that doesn't give the same results as the differential version.\n\nI'm stepping well beyond my area of expertise and need to stop lest I get sucked into a black hole.\n\nIn case this is of interest to someone else, with more knowledge, I am posting the WIP "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "https:\/\/github.com\/guitarvydas\/brusselator",
                                "text": "repository"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " here. See the README.md for usage."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
